But two obligations are essential ; if there is not one to novate, the attempted novation is null ; is there is one to novate, but the novating contract is void (e. g. ‘ si id quod tu mihi debeas, a peregrino, cum quo sponsus communio non est, spondes verbo stipulatus sim ³ Gaius iii. 179), the former is altogether unaffected.

The promise of a slave ordinarily created a natural obligation‚ and consequently, as Servius Sulpicius argued (Gaius, loc. cit.)‚ it is hard to see why it should have no novative effect3 the explanation given by Theophilus is ὅτι ποιεῖ refiert-imm οὗ μόνον τὸ τίκτεσθαι φυσικὴν ἐνοχὴν, ἀλλὰ καὶ τὸ ὑπεῖναι πρόσωπον· ἇπρόσωποι· δὲ ὀ δοῦλος.

The rule that, is the parties to the new contract are the same, a novation ensues only if it contains ‘ novi quid,’ holds only where the · novated obligation was itself verbal. 1f it had been otherwise, novation would have been disabled from discharging one of its most valued functions, viz. the substitution of obligations pursued by actions stricti iuris for obligations ensorceable only by actio ex fide bona. The Procu- lians were of opinion that the adiectio or detractio of a surety in the new contract was not sufficient to support a novation, Gaius iii. 178.

For condicio and dies see on Tit. 15. 2 and 4 supr.

Servius Sulpicius had held that a conditional stipulation novated an unconditional contract whether the condition was fulfined or not. Gaius (iii. 179) thought that the old contract subsisted until the condition os the new one was sulfilled, but suggests that if the creditor sued upon it before such fulfilment he might be met by exceptio doli or pacti, and this was soon recognised as law, Dig. 23. 3. 503 ib. 833 12. 1. 36 ς though Labeo (Dig. 2 3. 3. 80) had thought otherwise.

Among the praesumptiones or evidence upon which the jurists relied to prove that there was animus novandi was, according to the Sabinian school, the addition of a surety (cf. Dig. 2. 14. 30. 1) 3 for the presumptions against such intention see Dig. 46. 2. 6. pr. and 1. 3 45. 1. 58. Justinian's own enactment is in Cod. 8. 42. 8 ; his statement that, unless the inten- tion to novate was express (‘nisi ipsi specialiter remiserint quidem priorem obligationem et hoc expresserint, quod secundam magis pro anterioribus elegerint ’ Cod. loc cit.)‚ the two obligations should subsist side by side is apparently subject to the qualification that when one was fulfined the other was ipso sacto extinguished ; see Dig. 46. 2. 8. 5.
